## I. The Memo

On August 23, 1971, Lewis F. Powell Jr. — a corporate attorney, a board member of Philip Morris, a former president of the American Bar Association, and a man who had spent his career in the White male social and corporate elite of Richmond, Virginia — mailed a confidential memorandum to his friend Eugene B. Sydnor Jr., chairman of the Education Committee of the U.S. Chamber of Commerce. The memo was titled “Attack on American Free Enterprise System.” It was eight pages long. Two months later, on October 22, 1971, President Richard Nixon nominated Powell to the Supreme Court. The memo was not disclosed to the Senate during his confirmation proceedings. Powell was sworn in as an Associate Justice on January 7, 1972 — less than six months after delivering the document that would reshape the architecture of American power for half a century and beyond.

Powell’s argument was straightforward in its diagnosis and sweeping in its prescription. The American economic system, he wrote, was under broad attack — not merely from extremists of the left but from perfectly respectable elements of society: the college campus, the pulpit, the media, the intellectual and literary journals, the arts and sciences, and from politicians. He identified Ralph Nader’s consumer protection movement — which had triggered the American consumer movement after Nader’s 1965 exposé *Unsafe at Any Speed* put a focus on the auto industry putting profit ahead of safety — as the chief antagonist. Powell’s experiences as a corporate lawyer and a director on the board of Philip Morris made him a champion of the tobacco industry who railed against the growing scientific evidence linking smoking and cancer. The civil rights movement had disrupted Jim Crow across the South, drawing out and exposing the racist violence that had long enforced segregation and upsetting America’s all-White corporate suites and boardrooms. Anti-war protesters scorned the military-industrial complex. The environmental movement protested corporate pollution. Public health groups linked the tobacco industry to deadly illnesses.

Powell saw all of this as an existential threat to the free enterprise system — and his response was not a single campaign but an ecosystem. He called for the creation of a permanent intellectual infrastructure: a “faculty of scholars” who could be deployed to campuses, speakers’ bureaus, monitoring of textbooks and television content. He advocated “constant surveillance” of national television networks and textbooks. He urged the Chamber to insist on the right to be heard, on “equal time,” and to deploy “whatever degree of pressure — publicly and privately — may be necessary.” This would be “a long road,” Powell warned, “and not for the fainthearted.”

Powell understood that the project required institutional capture across multiple domains simultaneously. He identified the judiciary as perhaps the most important instrument for social, economic, and political change, citing the ACLU as a liberal entity that had experience promoting the appointment of sympathetic judges, and called for a similarly equipped conservative organization to take up the cause on behalf of business. He recommended using political influence to stem “the stampedes by politicians to support any legislation related to ‘consumerism’ or to the ‘environment’” — placing the word “environment” in derogatory quotation marks. He wrote that political power “is necessary; it must be assiduously cultivated; and when necessary, it must be used aggressively and with determination — without embarrassment and without the reluctance which has been so characteristic of American business.”

The memo was not the work of a fringe thinker. It was, as the Washington and Lee University archive describes it, both credited as having “changed America” and the single most requested document in the Lewis F. Powell Jr. Papers. Its influence is traceable through every major development in the conservative institutional project that followed.

In March 1973, the Chamber of Commerce’s Public Affairs Committee convened a three-day conference at Disney World’s Polynesian Resort billed as the first gathering of the “Task Force on the Powell Memorandum.” Sessions focused on enhancing the image of business, strategies for political action, and creating a long-term framework to expand corporate influence. The task force divided into subcommittees, each focused on a core tenet of the memo: education, communications, political action, and judicial action. They were encouraged to “blue sky” their ideas beyond the memo’s already ambitious scope.

The results were staggering in their scope and durability. Within a decade of the memo’s release, the number of companies with public affairs offices in Washington increased from 100 to over 500. The number of companies with registered lobbyists rose from 175 to nearly 2,500. The Heritage Foundation was established in 1973, funded initially by the Coors brewing family and Richard Mellon Scaife’s publishing enterprise. The Cato Institute followed. The American Enterprise Institute was revitalized. The Federalist Society, founded in 1982, began the systematic project of reshaping the federal judiciary that would produce the Roberts Court and, ultimately, the *Citizens United* decision — the case in which the Court, building on Powell’s own earlier opinion in *First National Bank of Boston v. Bellotti*, declared that corporate financial influence of elections by independent expenditures should be protected with the same vigor as individual speech.

By the close of the 1970s, the U.S. Chamber of Commerce had been transformed from a cautious, passive business group into a politically aggressive and ideologically driven machine, rebuilt to carry out the “careful long-range planning and implementation” Powell had urged. It became part of the broader vision he had imagined: an alliance of business interests and conservative political groups, united in opposition to the regulatory state and working together as a social movement for capitalism. Measured in money spent, the Chamber became the most powerful lobby in Washington — $770.6 million since 1998, over three times the amount spent by the next-largest spender, General Electric. The Chamber also reinforced its lobbying power by becoming one of the largest conduits of election-related “independent expenditures,” spending over $32.8 million on federal elections in 2010. It sponsors the Institute for Legal Reform, which has spearheaded the campaign for tort “reform” — making it more difficult for people who have been injured to sue the responsible corporations.

Charles Koch read the memo and concluded it didn’t go far enough. In a speech to the Institute for Humane Studies, which he had taken over in the early 1970s, Koch argued that Powell was wrong in assuming that most businesses believed in free enterprise, because Koch’s definition of that term was narrower still: he rejected the idea of equal opportunity laws, wage rules, and health and safety laws, framing them as inherently anti-capitalist. Koch’s agenda — operationalized over the following decades through the Koch network’s political spending infrastructure — eventually captured the Republican Party when it came to business deregulation. As journalist Nancy MacLean documented, the campaign amounted to a sustained effort to “save capitalism from democracy — permanently.” And as Jane Mayer and others have traced, the strategy worked: megacorporations now enjoy fewer regulations, lower taxes, more lobbyists, more businesspeople in power, and the ability to impede any policy perceived as hurting their bottom line — whether climate protections, health care reform, or privacy legislation.

The Powell Memo’s most consequential legacy, however, is not any single institution it produced. It is the *ecosystem* — the flywheel of compounding institutional power. A Heritage Foundation policy paper becomes a Federalist Society legal brief becomes a Supreme Court opinion becomes a media talking point becomes a campaign contribution. Each component reinforces the others. Each year’s investment compounds into the next year’s capacity. The result, more than fifty years later, is an institutional architecture so deeply embedded in the structure of American governance that it operates as the default — the regulatory environment, the judicial philosophy, the lobbying infrastructure, the media landscape — all shaped by a project that began with eight pages mailed to the Chamber of Commerce by a corporate lawyer who believed that American business was the true “forgotten man.”

Senator Sheldon Whitehouse, in his “Scheme” series of Senate floor speeches, placed the memo at the origin of what he described as a long-running, right-wing scheme to capture the Supreme Court through dark money. More than 50 years after Powell’s memo, the Heritage Foundation — the same organization born from Powell’s vision — produced Project 2025, a 900-page manual for transforming the executive branch. The through-line is direct, documented, and unbroken.

Powell did not call for surveillance of citizens. He called for surveillance of media, textbooks, and universities — the institutional spaces where public opinion was formed. His project was to ensure that those spaces produced opinion favorable to corporate interests. The irony that would take fifty years to fully materialize is that the institutional architecture he built — the deregulated marketplace, the captured judiciary, the weakened regulatory agencies, the blocked privacy legislation — would create the precise conditions under which a surveillance apparatus emerged that made his original project look quaint. Powell wanted to monitor television. His heirs built a system that monitors everyone, all the time, and sells the data to the government without a warrant.

