## II. The Loophole

The United States does not have a comprehensive federal data privacy law. This is not an oversight. It is not regulatory lag. It is the downstream product of the regulatory vacuum that Powell’s institutional project created and sustained across five decades.

The European Union’s General Data Protection Regulation, implemented in 2018, requires explicit and informed consent before personal data is collected. It applies to any entity that processes personal data in the context of activities in the EU or that targets EU individuals — without revenue thresholds, without processing thresholds, without broker thresholds. Violations carry administrative fines of up to €20 million or 4% of total worldwide annual turnover, whichever is higher.

The United States, by contrast, relies on what every analyst describes as a patchwork: sector-specific federal laws (HIPAA for health, FERPA for education, COPPA for children) and state-level legislation that varies wildly in scope and enforcement. As of 2026, only four states — California, Oregon, Texas, and Vermont — require data brokers to register with state agencies and disclose their activities. There is no federal framework governing the collection, sale, or use of personal data by commercial entities. The Consumer Financial Protection Bureau proposed a rule in December 2024 to limit the sale of sensitive personal information under the Fair Credit Reporting Act, but ultimately concluded that such a rule was “not necessary or appropriate at this time.” The CFPB under the Trump administration has since been functionally gutted.

And there is no federal law prohibiting law enforcement agencies from purchasing data that they would otherwise need a warrant to obtain.

This is the data broker loophole — and it is the gap through which the Fourth Amendment has been emptied of its practical meaning for millions of Americans.

The Supreme Court’s 2018 decision in *Carpenter v. United States* held that police need a warrant to obtain historical cell-site location information — the data generated as a cell phone automatically connects to nearby cell towers. The Court recognized that tracking a person’s movements over time is extremely invasive, that individuals have a reasonable expectation of privacy in the “all-encompassing record” of their whereabouts, and that a central aim of the Fourth Amendment is to “place obstacles in the way of a too permeating police surveillance.” The Court held that if law enforcement wants to obtain location information on a particular individual for seven days or more, it must have a warrant.

Federal agencies have argued that the *Carpenter* decision applies only to the specific type of location data at issue in that case — cell-site location information compelled from telecommunications companies — and that Fourth Amendment protections apply only when the government *compels* companies to disclose information, not when private companies voluntarily sell or disclose information to law enforcement. Based on this distinction, agencies have continued to purchase cell phone location data — without a warrant or any other legal process — in large volumes. The government’s position is that buying data is constitutionally different from seizing it. The practical effect is the same.

The industry that fills this loophole is worth over $250 billion. Data brokers — companies that collect, assemble, analyze, and sell personal information to create detailed profiles of individuals — are among the main purveyors in what the Brennan Center for Justice calls a “surveillance capitalism ecosystem.” They collect information from multiple sources: they pay app developers to install code that siphons users’ data, including location information; they use cookies and web trackers to capture online activity; they scrape information from social media platforms, often in violation of those platforms’ terms of service; and they purchase data from a wide range of companies, including internet service providers, car manufacturers, advertisers, utility companies, supermarkets, and others.

A Virginia-based company called Fog Data Science sells a service that it bills as allowing police to see where a person was at any point in time over the past several years — including homes, churches, workplaces, and health clinics. The data is collected through a chain of businesses: personal location data is gathered via thousands of common apps on Android and iOS phones, passed through intermediaries, and ends up with Fog, which resells it to law enforcement through a subscription-based search engine called Fog Reveal. An investigation by the Electronic Frontier Foundation — conducted over several months through more than 100 public records requests — found that Fog has past or current contracts with at least 18 local, state, and federal law enforcement agencies. Records show that Fog and some police agencies did not believe this surveillance implicated people’s Fourth Amendment rights and did not obtain a warrant before searching through people’s location data. And glaringly absent from the public records were any documents establishing policies or other limits about when and how police could deploy this massive digital dragnet.

Among the EFF’s findings: In Chino, California, police used Fog’s service to do massive sweeps determining who was near minor theft and burglary scenes. In a rural Missouri murder investigation, Fog’s service was used to track a babysitter who was never a suspect — police built an extensive profile of her movements and activities before learning through witness testimony that the victim’s wife was responsible. In Greensboro, North Carolina, a crime analysis supervisor raised red flags about the tool’s constitutionality and later quit after his warnings were ignored. Fog’s subscription costs less than $10,000 — mass surveillance on a municipal budget.

The federal agencies are doing the same thing at scale. U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement began purchasing access to cell phone location data through a data brokerage company called Venntel in 2018. The data had been collected from popular cell phone apps — weather, shopping, and video game apps. ICE used Venntel’s service to track the movements of cell phone users near the southern border. At one point, ICE discovered phones moving back and forth across a closed portion of the border in a straight line — eventually determining they were traveling through an underground smuggling tunnel from a private home in Mexico to a closed Kentucky Fried Chicken restaurant in Arizona. ICE passed this information to the local police department, which made an apparently pretextual traffic stop, finding large quantities of drugs. The San Luis police kept any mention of the cell phone tracking out of their records and initially attributed the stop to an “equipment violation.” Government agents often obscure their purchases of constitutionally protected information by recreating the purchased information through more traditional means — a process that raises obvious concerns about deception and the avoidance of public scrutiny.

The Department of Defense purchased location data from popular Muslim prayer and Qur’an apps and dating apps through defense contractors. The FBI renegotiated its purchase contract with a data broker around the time of the Black Lives Matter protests in 2020. Cell phone data was allegedly used to track Black Lives Matter protesters. Several members of Congress made official inquiries into how this data was utilized. The Brennan Center documented the use of purchased data to target religious groups and protesters, emphasizing the critical importance of the Fourth Amendment in protecting against discriminatory policing and the chilling effect that unrestricted surveillance has on religious freedom and the right to dissent.

When Senator Ron Wyden asked FBI Director Kash Patel in early 2026 whether the Bureau would commit to not buying Americans’ location data, Patel declined, saying the FBI “uses all tools” and that it purchases “commercially available information that’s consistent with the Constitution.”

Privacy advocate Jake Laperruque, deputy director of the Security and Surveillance Project at the Center for Democracy and Technology, noted that purchasing bulk data from data brokers is “very much not what Congress intended when it said we are banning bulk collection. It wasn’t, you know, ‘do bulk collection, but also pay taxpayer money for it.’ It was ‘don’t do bulk collection.’”

Anthropic CEO Dario Amodei warned in a February 2026 statement that records the government can purchase can be used by AI to assemble “a comprehensive picture of any person’s life — automatically and at massive scale.” His unwillingness to allow Anthropic’s technology to be used for domestic mass surveillance or autonomous weapons led to a major confrontation with the Pentagon, which responded that a private company cannot dictate how the government lawfully uses its technology. Anthropic was designated a supply chain risk.

Montana became the first state to close the data broker loophole for law enforcement in May 2025, prohibiting police from purchasing citizens’ data when they would ordinarily need a warrant to access it. The bipartisan Fourth Amendment Is Not For Sale Act passed the House in 2024 with near-unanimous support from the Judiciary Committee, but stalled in the Senate. The Brennan Center, the Project on Government Oversight, and over 130 civil society organizations have urged Congress to close the loophole as part of FISA Section 702 reauthorization. As of April 2026, the reauthorization debate remains unresolved.

Representative Warren Davidson, a Republican from Ohio, told NPR that the data broker issue “doesn’t break on party lines” — describing the practice as “collecting data that really you would never get a warrant for, that kind of a broad dragnet sweep under normal warrant requirements.” He teamed up with conservative Senator Mike Lee and Democrats Zoe Lofgren and Ron Wyden on bipartisan FISA reform legislation. The coalition exists. The legislation exists. Congress has not acted.

The loophole persists because the institutional architecture that Powell built is designed to ensure that it persists. The lobbying infrastructure delays legislation. The captured judiciary interprets existing law narrowly. The weakened regulatory agencies lack enforcement capacity. And the technology integrates more deeply into the infrastructure of daily life with each passing year, raising the cost of regulation and lowering the political will to attempt it.

