## III. The Convergence Abroad

If the American trajectory is the product of the Powell Memo’s institutional capture and the data broker loophole’s commercial exploitation, the global trajectory reveals something more disturbing: a convergence across political systems that defies the stated justifications of each but produces the same material outcome.

The European Union built the most comprehensive privacy framework in the world — the GDPR, which set a global standard that influenced legislation from Brazil to India to California. For a decade, it served as the democratic counterweight to the American surveillance model. That counterweight is now being actively dismantled.

In November 2025, the European Commission published the Digital Omnibus — a package of reforms to the GDPR, the ePrivacy Directive, and the AI Act, presented as simplification for small and medium enterprises. European Digital Rights described it as “a massive reopening of EU’s core digital protections — a move that risks dismantling the very foundation of human rights and tech policy in the EU.” The EFF called it a proposal that “promises red tape cuts but guts GDPR privacy rights.” Amnesty International described it as a “coordinated effort to weaken corporate accountability,” noting the false dichotomy between regulation and innovation “championed by Big Tech, who seek a rules-free environment that prioritizes profit at any cost.”

The European Data Protection Board and the European Data Protection Supervisor issued a joint opinion strongly urging the co-legislators not to adopt the proposed changes to the definition of personal data, warning that the changes “go far beyond a targeted or technical amendment of the GDPR” and “would result in significantly narrowing the concept of personal data.” They specifically warned that the European Commission “should not be entrusted to decide by an implementing act what is no longer personal data after pseudonymisation as it directly affects the scope of application of EU data protection law.”

The proposed changes would narrow the definition of personal data — meaning that pseudonymous identifiers like ad IDs and cookies could lose GDPR protection, paving the way for more tracking and profiling. A new “legitimate interest” exception would allow companies to use personal data, including some sensitive information, for AI training without explicit consent. The ePrivacy framework — the law governing how companies access data on users’ devices — would be absorbed into the GDPR under conditions that shift Europe from an opt-in system to something closer to opt-out. Article 22 of the GDPR, which limits automated decision-making, would be reframed as a broader permission for automation — “turning a prohibition with exceptions into an authorisation subject to conditions,” making it easier to deploy automated systems in contexts where human review currently matters.

Technologist Robin Berjon warned that the proposed reforms “go beyond mere simplification. American tech monopolies and intelligence agencies are the biggest beneficiaries of the surveillance economy and these changes strengthen their hand to instead actively sabotage European businesses and national security.”

The timing is not coincidental. The Commission’s Executive Vice President met with top U.S. tech executives to pitch a more business-friendly Europe. The reforms followed a report by former Italian Prime Minister Mario Draghi warning that Europe’s complex laws were stifling innovation. The language of competitiveness — the same rhetorical framework that the Powell project deployed against American regulation fifty years ago — is now being used to dismantle the one democratic privacy framework that had achieved meaningful protection at scale.

Meanwhile, even the existing GDPR has gaps in its coverage of data brokers. As Lawfare documented, the GDPR framework can leave legal and conceptual gaps when it comes to the role of parties that gather, process, generate, and transmit data — such as the potential lack of coverage when one broker sells data it did not collect itself to another data broker. European regulators, focused overwhelmingly on American Big Tech companies like Meta and Alphabet, have paid less attention to the data brokerage industry operating within Europe itself. An RTÉ investigation in Ireland found that reporters gained access to brokered data on tens of thousands of smartphones — available for purchase — that could trace individual devices between residential addresses, prisons, health clinics, mental health facilities, military bases, and the Irish parliament.

China’s Social Credit System and India’s Aadhaar biometric identification program represent the authoritarian and democratic ends of the same spectrum. Ralph Schroeder’s research at Oxford identifies them as “two cases of the most rapid capture of personal data about national populations in history.” Both governments claim participation is voluntary while linking vital services to registration. India’s Aadhaar, launched in 2009 as a voluntary system to deliver welfare benefits, now covers 99% of the population — and has been made mandatory for maintaining bank accounts, insurance policies, and paying taxes, despite the absence of adequate legislative measures to protect the data. Security officials attempted to use the Aadhaar database to identify “criminals,” and intelligence officials acknowledged that the welfare claim was a pretext — the system’s purpose was to flush out illegal immigrants.

China’s Social Credit System, while not the monolithic scoring mechanism that Western media sometimes portrays — it remains fragmented across localities and centrally managed entries are still manually entered by officials — nevertheless represents the explicit integration of behavioral surveillance into governance. In 2024, China’s National Development and Reform Commission issued plans for more complete credit legislation, unified codes, and strengthened platform infrastructure. Over 200 million surveillance cameras, augmented by AI facial recognition, are deployed across the country. The government continues to track online behavior. The 2025 guidelines stressed safeguards against excessive collection — a tacit acknowledgment that excessive collection is the default.

The justifications differ across systems. The United States deregulates in the name of market freedom. The European Union deregulates in the name of competitiveness. China builds social credit in the name of social harmony. India deploys Aadhaar in the name of financial inclusion. The trajectory is identical: states and corporations accumulating unprecedented surveillance capacity over populations with diminishing oversight. The distinction between a democratic government purchasing your location data from a broker and an authoritarian government collecting it directly is a distinction of method, not of outcome. The citizen is rendered transparent. The state is rendered opaque. The asymmetry is the same.

