## IV. The Diagnostician

Into this architecture stepped Bruce Schneier — a security technologist, Harvard Kennedy School lecturer, EFF board member, and the author who has spent twenty years producing the most precise diagnosis of the surveillance state available in the English language, and who has watched every one of his warnings validated while none of his proposed solutions have been implemented at federal scale.

Schneier’s 2015 book *Data and Goliath: The Hidden Battles to Collect Your Data and Control Your World* laid out the structural analysis in three parts: what’s happening, why it matters, and what to do about it. His framework rests on several interlocking arguments.

First, Schneier defines all personal data collection as surveillance — whether gathered for law enforcement, intelligence, commercial use, or no particular reason. Under this definition, the NSA and FBI perform surveillance, but so do Google, Sears, and the local liquor store. This is not rhetorical inflation. It is a structural observation: the data flows are fungible, the systems are interoperable, and the distinction between corporate and government surveillance collapses when the government can simply purchase what corporations collect.

Second, Schneier argues that corporate surveillance and government surveillance are symbiotic, not separate — intertwined, supporting one another. The data broker industry is the connective tissue. Corporations harvest the raw material. Governments purchase it. The Fourth Amendment’s protections are emptied not by a constitutional amendment but by a commercial transaction.

Third, Schneier reframes the fundamental debate: the real choice is not security versus privacy but liberty versus control. “Tyranny, whether it arises under threat of foreign physical attack or under constant domestic authoritative scrutiny, is still tyranny. Liberty requires security without intrusion, security plus privacy. Widespread police surveillance is the very definition of a police state.”

Fourth, Schneier demonstrates that mass surveillance is not merely invasive but empirically ineffective for its stated purpose. The Privacy and Civil Liberties Oversight Board found the Section 215 bulk metadata collection program to be nearly useless as well as likely illegal.

Fifth, and most fundamentally, Schneier identifies the power asymmetry as the structural core: “Data is power. Any entity, whether public or private, that holds data about individuals has some ability to understand, predict, and manipulate their behavior.”

The book’s proposed solutions — stronger privacy laws, limits on data collection, corporate responsibility, individual action — were principled, thoughtful, and, by Schneier’s own admission, not all readily achievable. The Federation of American Scientists reviewed it favorably, noting that Schneier’s core objective was to “preserve, or to restore, a domain of personal privacy that is impervious to unwanted intrusion.”

Every warning in *Data and Goliath* has been validated. The surveillance apparatus has expanded in every dimension Schneier identified. The data broker loophole remains open. No comprehensive federal privacy law has been enacted. The corporate-government surveillance symbiosis has deepened. The book was an intellectual breakthrough that produced no structural change — the Occupy Wall Street of cybersecurity policy.

In October 2025, Schneier published *Rewiring Democracy: How AI Will Transform Our Politics, Government, and Citizenship*, co-authored with Nathan Sanders. The book examines how AI is transforming democracy across five domains — politics, legislating, administration, the judiciary, and citizenship — and proposes a four-part plan: resist inappropriate uses of AI, seek responsible uses of AI in governance, reform the ecosystem of AI, and renovate democracy to prepare it for AI. Schneier himself acknowledges the last one feels most urgent. He states the power concentration problem directly: “We already know the answer, because we’ve seen it happen: in big tech in general and with social media in particular. The powerful get more powerful, and then use that power to enact legislative changes that further protect that power.”

The book was published on October 21, 2025. By that date, DOGE had already been operating for months, doing exactly what the book warned about in the abstract.

On June 5, 2025, Schneier testified before the House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform at a hearing titled “The Federal Government in the Age of Artificial Intelligence.” He identified what he called the “DOGE approach” to data handling, with four distinct features: data consolidation — exfiltrating and connecting massive U.S. databases to create a single pool of data covering all citizens; reduced security protocols — removing access controls and audit logs, creating unmonitored copies of data, exposing sensitive data to cloud-based tools, seeking maximally permissive data access waivers, and eliminating previously required security protocols for vetting staff; AI training and processing — using AI tools to process data outside carefully monitored environments; and the offering of consolidated data to private companies such as Palantir.

Schneier told Congress: “You all need to assume that adversaries have copies of all the data DOGE has exfiltrated and has established access into all the networks that DOGE has removed security controls from.” He warned that any military action against the United States could be preceded by the zeroing-out of bank accounts for military and political leaders — made possible by the consolidation of Treasury and OPM data.

He warned that access to Americans’ data could give private companies significant advantages in training AI systems and setting business strategy — and that without proper oversight, this access could lead to private companies profiting from sensitive information or foreign governments exploiting vulnerabilities. He noted that the safeguards protecting government data were built over years to protect Americans, “but these protections are already eroding.”

The other witnesses at the hearing talked about how cool AI was — and sometimes about how cool their own companies were. Schneier’s testimony was not mentioned in the Oversight Committee’s official summary of the hearing. Representative Nancy Mace, chairing the subcommittee, opened by focusing on AI’s potential as a productivity tool. As *The Register* reported, Schneier “played the skunk at the garden party.”

Schneier’s career trajectory is the case study that proves the structural asymmetry. *Data and Goliath* (2015) diagnosed the problem. *Rewiring Democracy* (2025) proposed the counter-strategy. Congressional testimony (2025) delivered the warning to the institution with the power to act. The institution did not act. It did not even record that the warning was given.

