## V. The General Magic Parallel

There is a company — dead since 2004, liquidated, its patents sold to Paul Allen — that illuminates Anthropic’s trajectory with the precision of a parable. It was called General Magic.

General Magic was co-founded in 1990 by Bill Atkinson, Andy Hertzfeld, and Marc Porat — members of the original Macintosh team who spun out of Apple because they believed the parent organization couldn’t see what was coming. Known as the Paradigm project inside Apple, the team struggled for resources against a management that remained generally uninterested. Eventually they approached CEO John Sculley with the idea of spinning off as a separate company.

What General Magic built was, by any honest accounting, the smartphone — fifteen years before the iPhone. The company developed precursors to USB, software modems, small touchscreens, touchscreen controller ASICs, multimedia email, networked games, streaming television, and early e-commerce. Marc Porat wrote in his notebook: “A small device that will be your phone, your wallet, and your window to the world.” In approximately 1994, Porat was filmed predicting “smart phones, smart pagers, and maybe even things like intelligent watches” — describing both the iPhone and Apple Watch decades ahead of time.

By 1992, Sony, Motorola, Matsushita, Philips, and AT&T were partners and investors. The company went public in 1995 — with no shipped product or revenue — at a valuation of $834 million, raising over $90 million. It was a unicorn before the term existed.

And it failed. The Sony Magic Link, its flagship device, cost $800 (approximately $1,600 in 2022 dollars). It weighed 1.5 pounds. Processors couldn’t keep up. Battery life was abysmal. Fewer than 3,000 units were sold — mostly to family and friends.

But the failure was not merely technical. It was structural, and the structural failures map onto Anthropic’s present with uncomfortable precision.

The parent betrayal: Sculley, who was on General Magic’s board and had access to its work, launched the Apple Newton at CES 1993 — a competing device that, although technically inferior, stole the media oxygen. General Magic’s team was blindsided. Hertzfeld said later: “They were our closest partner, who really gave us our life. And so when we found out they were trying to kill us, we felt completely betrayed.” Anthropic’s parent — OpenAI, the organization its founders built — has become its primary competitor, systematically abandoning the safety principles that motivated Anthropic’s founding while publicly claiming safety leadership. By end of 2025, only two of OpenAI’s original eleven co-founders remained full-time — Sam Altman and Wojciech Zaremba.

The alliance problem: General Magic assembled an unwieldy alliance of companies to manufacture and distribute its product — AT&T, Apple, Motorola, Sony, Panasonic, Phillips — some of them natural enemies. The complexity was enormous. Anthropic runs on AWS, Google TPUs, and NVIDIA GPUs. Amazon remains the primary cloud provider and training partner. But Amazon has its own Titan models. Google has Gemini. The alliance partners are simultaneously investors, cloud providers, and competitors with their own AI ambitions.

The infrastructure mismatch: General Magic built a luxury Ferrari, but the world didn’t have asphalt yet. The infrastructure — broadband, processors, batteries — did not exist to support the vision. Anthropic’s safety mission faces the inverse mismatch: the infrastructure for surveillance exists, and the institutional capture that prevents the regulatory infrastructure for safety is already in place.

The timing problem: General Magic arrived too early — the market didn’t exist. Anthropic may be arriving too late — the institutional architecture that would need to support “responsible AI” as a binding regulatory framework has been captured by the Powell project before Anthropic’s safety research could be translated into binding law.

General Magic’s people went on to build the actual future. Tony Fadell created the iPod and iPhone. Andy Rubin created Android. Pierre Omidyar wrote the code for eBay while sitting in the General Magic office. The company died. The vision lived. But it lived inside other companies that did not share General Magic’s original values.

Anthropic’s most probable long-term trajectory — if the safety mission is subordinated to the survival imperative — follows the same arc. The safety research becomes the intellectual foundation for whatever “responsible AI framework” the captured regulatory state eventually mandates: a framework written by the think tanks Powell’s infrastructure built, enforced by the agencies those think tanks staffed, designed to protect incumbents while wearing the language of Anthropic’s mission like borrowed clothing. The vision lives. The company that held it is either absorbed, compromised, or made niche. The gap between the two is where the policy debt accrues.

As of April 2026, Anthropic has overtaken OpenAI in annualized revenue — over $30 billion against OpenAI’s $24-25 billion. Claude Code holds 54% of the enterprise coding market. All seven co-founders remain. The safety research is ongoing. And the Pentagon has designated the company a supply chain risk for maintaining its principles. The revenue buys time. It does not change the underlying dynamics.

