## VI. The Sovereign Algorithm’s Contractor

If the Powell Memo built the institutional architecture of capture, and the data broker loophole built the commercial infrastructure of surveillance, and Schneier diagnosed the crisis with precision that the system was structurally designed to ignore, and Anthropic attempted to build a responsible alternative inside a market that punishes responsibility — then Palantir Technologies is the entity that fused all of these threads into a single operational system at the heart of the state.

Palantir was co-founded in 2003 by Peter Thiel — a venture capitalist, PayPal co-founder, and early Facebook investor who would become one of the most consequential political donors of the twenty-first century — with early funding from In-Q-Tel, the CIA’s venture capital arm. The company’s software — Gotham for intelligence and defense, Foundry for commercial and government operations — integrates disparate data streams into unified analytical platforms. Its original purpose was counterterrorism. Its current purpose is everything.

In 2025, Palantir’s federal contracts nearly doubled, rising to $970.5 million. Multi-year contract ceilings awarded in 2025 alone totaled over $13.7 billion — $84.26 per American taxpayer if fully exercised. Revenue grew 6.5 times in six years, reaching $4.48 billion in FY2025 — up 56% in a single year. Twenty-two years after its founding, Palantir’s software runs inside the CIA, the Pentagon, ICE, the IRS, the CDC, the Army, and dozens of other agencies. CEO Alex Karp received $6.8 billion in compensation in 2024, making him the highest-paid public company CEO that year.

The contracts constitute the operational architecture of what “Jus Algoritmi” calls the sovereign algorithm:

The U.S. Army awarded Palantir an enterprise agreement worth up to $10 billion over a decade, consolidating 75 contracts into a single deal that makes Palantir the backbone data platform for Army modernization — integrating Foundry, TITAN, and Vantage products across Army operations to aggregate sensor data, logistics, personnel readiness, and intelligence into a single operational picture. Once the Army’s data infrastructure runs on Palantir, switching costs become effectively infinite. This is a generational lock-in.

The Pentagon formalized Palantir’s Maven system — originally a 2017 project to use AI to process surveillance imagery — as a long-term, department-wide operational capability. Project Maven evolved from an experimental tool into a broader military intelligence and targeting platform that fuses data from multiple sensors to identify objects, assess threats, and support operational decisions. Maven-related contracts include a five-year, $480 million Army contract in 2024, a roughly $100 million follow-on expansion later that year, and a 2025 contract modification valued at up to $795 million.

ICE awarded Palantir a $30 million no-bid contract to build an “Immigration Lifecycle Operating System” — ImmigrationOS — designed to track self-deportations, help select targets for arrests, and create an “Immigration Lifecycle Process” to increase the efficiency of deportations.

Palantir employees were embedded at the IRS alongside DOGE staff to build a unified API layer across all IRS databases — creating a single access point to every tax return filed in the United States: Social Security numbers, tax returns, employment records, bank information, and filing history. Multiple members of Congress allege this violates Internal Revenue Code Sections 6103 and 7213A — post-Watergate laws specifically enacted to prevent the weaponization of taxpayer data. Senators Ron Wyden, Elizabeth Warren, and Edward Markey, along with Representative Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez, have formally demanded answers from Palantir CEO Alex Karp. Wyden stated: “Palantir is one of the companies making a lot of money out of this. There are privacy problems with what they’re doing. This has been a great, as I call it, a great harvest for these kind of technology operations and virtually no accountability.”

The Treasury Department subsequently announced it had awarded a contract to Palantir to create a “unified API layer” — formalizing what had begun as an ad hoc DOGE-driven project.

Palantir has also cultivated deep ties with the Israeli military. After announcing a “strategic partnership” with Israel in January 2024, the company’s involvement expanded to include integrating intercepted communications, satellite material, and other digital data sources to help produce targeting databases for the Israeli military. Amnesty International stated that “Palantir has a track record of flagrantly disregarding international law and standards, both in the violations of the human rights of migrants in the United States, to which it risks contributing to, and its ongoing supply of artificial intelligence products and services to the Israeli military and intelligence services that are linked to Israel’s ongoing genocide in Gaza.”

And then, in April 2026, Palantir published its manifesto.

