## VII. The Manifesto

On April 20, 2026, Palantir posted a 22-point summary of *The Technological Republic: Hard Power, Soft Belief, and the Future of the West*, co-authored by CEO Alex Karp and head of corporate affairs Nicholas Zamiska, to its X account. The post has accumulated over 32 million views.

*The Technological Republic* — a #1 New York Times bestseller, an NPR staff top pick for 2025, praised by George Will as the most sweeping cultural critique since Allan Bloom’s *The Closing of the American Mind* — is, in its own framing, “a passionate call for the West to wake up to our new reality.” In its critics’ framing, it is something else entirely.

The manifesto’s core arguments:

“Silicon Valley owes a moral debt to the country that made its rise possible. The engineering elite of Silicon Valley has an affirmative obligation to participate in the defense of the nation.”

“The limits of soft power, of soaring rhetoric alone, have been exposed. The ability of free and democratic societies to prevail requires something more than moral appeal. It requires hard power, and hard power in this century will be built on software.”

“The question is not whether A.I. weapons will be built; it is who will build them and for what purpose. Our adversaries will not pause to indulge in theatrical debates about the merits of developing technologies with critical military and national security applications. They will proceed.”

“National service should be a universal duty.”

“Not all cultures are equal. Some have proved middling, and worse, regressive and harmful.”

In a 2025 NYT DealBook Summit interview, Karp stated: “No one would listen to the superiority of our ideas if our ability to organize in violence was inferior… Every single person in the world believes this outside of the faculty of Harvard. And certainly our adversaries know to be true.” He explained his political priorities: “I care about two issues: I care about immigration and reestablishing the deterrent capacity of America… On those two issues, this president [Trump] has performed.”

The manifesto has been described by Al Jazeera as “an AI-driven threat to humanity’s existence” and “technofascism.” *The Nation* called it a “self-serving broadside steeped in oligarchic hubris and authoritarian nihilism.” Dave Karpf, associate professor at George Washington University, wrote in TechPolicy.Press that “there is nothing in this ‘America First’-sounding manifesto that wouldn’t fit comfortably within a modern-day Mussolini regime.” Engadget described it as reading “like the ramblings of a comic book villain.”

But the manifesto’s significance is not its rhetoric. It is its structural position in the architecture this chapter has been tracing. Read the Powell Memo and read *The Technological Republic* side by side. The through-line is direct:

Powell, 1971: American business is under attack. The engineering of political power — through universities, media, courts, and legislatures — is a moral obligation of the corporate class. The regulatory state must be weakened. Corporate interests must capture the institutions of democratic governance.

Karp, 2025: Silicon Valley has failed its moral obligation to the nation. Hard power must be built on software. AI weapons must be built by American companies. Some cultures are regressive. The limits of soft power have been exposed. National service should be universal. Technology companies must participate in defense.

Powell called for corporate capture of democratic institutions to protect free enterprise. Karp calls for the fusion of Silicon Valley and the military-intelligence apparatus to project hard power. Powell wanted to monitor textbooks. Karp builds the systems that monitor populations. Powell wanted to shape the judiciary. Karp builds the platforms that the judiciary cannot yet govern. Powell’s project created the regulatory vacuum. Karp’s company fills it — with software that tracks immigrants, consolidates taxpayer data, identifies bombing targets, and processes the raw material of democratic citizenship through algorithms that no elected body controls and no affected person can appeal.

The Powell Memo was a confidential strategy document for the Chamber of Commerce. *The Technological Republic* is a New York Times bestseller posted as a 22-point manifesto on a platform with 32 million views. The quiet part is now the loud part. The institutional capture is so complete that the beneficiaries no longer need to hide the architecture. They can publish it, promote it, and profit from it — while the company simultaneously operates ImmigrationOS for ICE, embeds employees in the IRS, and holds a $10 billion contract to become the operating system of the U.S. Army.

